{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"90594f93-a66a-42ab-aad0-e204a42e066a","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, the OS automatically generates a crash report. You can find it in:\n\n**Crash Reports location:**\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions).\n\n**To view them:**\n- Open **Console.app** → Crash Reports (in the sidebar)\n- Or browse the directory directly: `ls ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n**For core dumps (optional):**\n```bash\n# Enable core dumps (disabled by default on macOS)\nulimit -c unlimited\n# Cores go to /cores/core.<pid>\n```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report includes the faulting thread, stack trace, and register state — often sufficient for diagnosing NativeAOT crashes without `createdump`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e066a7eb-2cf5-48f9-8fdb-17776299d024","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps or crash reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` is not available. This is a knowledge question - I don't need to search any codebase for this. I can answer directly from my knowledge about macOS crash reporting.","outputTokens":307,"requestId":"501A:2CDF90:26FE0F:307FE0:69F55450"},"id":"035912a9-849e-4534-a385-0b0f2231200b","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:33:13.646Z","parentId":"be9ed9ec-f454-4b3c-94eb-aaaf54593ee3"}
